1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 ({Remarkably, Aronian refrains from} 4. d5 {
when after} exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O {he had
been successful with white, while Topalov had lost with black in recent games.}
Re8 ({This is considered slightly more accurate than} 9... a6 10. a4 Re8 {when
after} 11. Bf4 {Black is more or less confined to embark the slightly exotic
line} Ne4 $5 {Aronian,L (2759)-Carlsen,M (2693)/Elista 2007/CBM 119/[Marin] 
(1-0, 66)}) 10. Bf4 Bg4 $5 {Eljanov,P (2692)-Topalov,V (2780)/Wijk aan Zee
2008/[Marin] (1-0, 46).  Aronian's choice may have been dictated by practical
reasoning: once Topalov is ready to play the Benoni again, he must have found
an improvement somewhere, or, who knows, an entire new plan.}) 4... cxd4 5.
Nxd4 Bb4+ {An open invitation to the fianchetto Nimzoindian.} 6. Bd2 {The
psychological duel continues and, once again, it seems that Topalov emerges as
a moral winner..} ({With reversed, colours, the position after} 6. Nc3 {(true,
via genuine Nimzo Indian move order) had occurred twice between the same
players and Topalov won each time.} O-O (6... Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9.
Qf3 {Topalov,V (2780)-Aronian,L (2739)/Morelia/Linares 2008 (1-0, 35)}) 7. Bg2
d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qb3 {Topalov,V (2801)-Aronian,L (2752)/Morelia/Linares 2006/
CBM 112/[Gavrikov] (1-0, 76)}) 6... Be7 {This method is frequently seen in
modern chess, in openings such as the Queen's Indian, the Catalan and, of
course, Bogo Indian. Apparently, Black has lost a tempo, but White will have
difficulties finding a good square for his queen's bishop, which stands in the
way of the own queen.} 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. Bc3 {The bishop's situation is not that
bad now, but usually this is the best square for the knight, keeping the
d5-square under severe control.} O-O 9. O-O d5 {The logical consequence of
Black's previous play. With a white knight on c3, this move would leave Black
with a weak pawn on d5 after cxd5.} 10. Nd2 Bd7 {A simple developing move,
inviting White to define his plans.} ({The main alternative is} 10... Qb6 11.
e3 ({Despite his defeat, Gavrikov repeated the line in a later rapid game. The
player with White did not know the theory of this variation too well and had
to improvise, which he did relatively well:} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 exd5 13.
N2b3 Bh3 14. Re1 Rfe8 15. Rc1 Rac8 16. Qd3 Bf8 17. Qb5 {After the exchange of
queens, the weakness of the g2-square becomes less relevant and White can
enjoy his stability on the dark squares with chances for a small, but stable
plus.} Qxb5 18. Nxb5 a6 19. N5d4 Ne5 20. f3 Bd7 21. Kf2 Nc4 22. e3 b5 23. a3 g6
24. Na5 Bh6 25. Nxc4 dxc4 {Black has improved his structure, but White
maintains his control in the centre.} 26. Rcd1 Bf8 27. Nc2 Bc6 28. Nb4 Re6 29.
Nxc6 Rexc6 30. Rd7 R6c7 31. Red1 Be7 $14 {Marin,M-Gavrikov,V/WorldChessNetwork.
com 2005 (0-1, 75). White's position is more active, but Black's queenside
majority, as well as the fact that White's pawns on this wing are situated on
dark squares offer Black some counterchances.}) 11... Bd7 12. a3 dxc4 13. Nxc4
Qa6 14. Qb3 {It is obvious now that the early development of Black's queen has
helped White win time for the coordination of his forces.} Nd5 15. Nxc6 Bxc6
16. Bd4 Rfd8 17. Rfc1 Ba4 18. Qa2 b6 19. b3 Be8 20. Qb2 Bf8 21. e4 Ne7 22. a4
$14 {Jussupow,A (2645)-Gavrikov,V (2550)/Minsk 1987/URS-ch (1-0, 42). with
domination for White.}) 11. cxd5 {Finally releasing the tension.} ({The
willing retreat} 11. N4b3 $146 {failed to impress in Huebner,R (2585)-Oral,T 
(2521)/Baden 1999/CBM 071/[Ribli] (1/2-1/2, 51)  White avoids possible
simplifications with ...Nxd4 and ...Bc6. He has the good Catalan bishop on g2,
but has problems with piece coordination on the queenside. Weiß vermeidet
mögliche Vereinfachungen mit ...Nxd4 und ...Bc6. Er besitzt den guten
katalanischen Läufer auf g2, hat aber am Damenflügel Probleme mit der
Figurenkoordination.}) ({However,} 11. Rc1 {, which also continues the
development without discarding White's intentions, deserves serious attention.}
Nb4 {Black is incompletly developed yet, which makes this knight jump look
premature.} ({The neutral} 11... Re8 {failed to equalize completely after} 12.
e4 {. Finally a concrete decision.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bc6 15. Qxd8
Rexd8 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Rfd1 $14 {Romero Holmes,A
(2550)-Suba,M (2498)/Almeria 2003/CBM 095 ext (1-0, 46). and White's rather
symbolic advantage eventually was converted into a win.}) ({The drawback of
Suba's move is that the rook is not doing much on e8 and it caused further
loss of time. Therefore,} 11... Rc8 $5 {, consolidating the c6-square in order
to avoid the creation of a weakness on that square, may be Black's best
solution.}) 12. Nc2 a5 (12... Nxa2 {looks risky, but leads to unclear
consequences, for instance} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Ra1 Qa5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Ne3
Bxb2 17. Qc2 Bxa1 18. Rxa1 Nb4 19. Rxa5 Nxc2 20. Nxc2 Rfc8 21. Ra2 Bf5 22. Nd4
Rc1+ 23. Nf1 $13 {Black is at least OK from a material point of view, but his
queenside pawns are not dangerous yet. However, White will need some time to
get rid of the back rank pin. Personally, I would prefer White, but am
convinced that the position remains double-edged.[%cal Gf2f3,Gg1f2,Gf1e3]}) 13.
a3 Nxc2 14. Qxc2 Bc6 15. Rfd1 Qb6 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. e4 Ng4 18. Rf1 Bc6 19. h3
Nf6 20. Nc4 Qb5 21. Ne5 $14 {Schlosser,P (2560)-Kosten,A (2540)/Austria 2003/
CBM 097 ext (1-0, 46). Again, White's position is more active in the presence
of almost symmetrical structure.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 {Catalan opening
players know that sometimes it is essential to part with the pride of their
position, in order to achieve certain strategic aims, or avoid strategic
problems. Here, Black will be left with a well-blocked isolani, while
otherwise the exchange on c3 would cause White problems on the dark squares.}
exd5 13. Qb3 {White immediately puts pressure on the b7- and d5-pawns, aiming
to cause some strategic concession from Black's part.} (13. N2f3 Re8 (13... Bh3
$5 14. Re1 Re8 {looks more restrictive.}) 14. Qb3 Bh3 15. Rfd1 $1 {The rook
stands better here than on e1.} Qd7 16. Rd3 Rad8 17. Rad1 Qc8 18. R1d2 $13 {
Seirawan,Y-Benjamin,J/Philadelphia 1986/Inf 42. The position does not
essentially differ from that arising in our main game.}) 13... Bf6 14. N2f3 Bg4
$5 $146 {A strong novelty.} ({Previously, the tempting} 14... Bh3 {had been
played. Black wins a tempo for the purpose of defending his attacked pawns,
but, generally speaking, the bishop is not doing much on h3, since the
attacking prospects are not too realistic for Black.} 15. Rfd1 Qd7 $6 (15...
Rb8 16. Nb5 $14 {would provoke the favourable exchange of the dark-squared
bishops.}) 16. Nxc6 $1 Bxc3 (16... bxc6 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qc3 $16) 17. Nce5 $1
Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qe6 19. Rxd5 $16 {Morovic Fernandez,I (2535)-Suba,M (2550)/New
York 1988/CBM 008 (1-0, 36)}) 15. Rfd1 ({One of the tactical points is that
after} 15. Qxb7 {Black gets his pawn back with} Nxd4 16. Nxd4 (16. Bxd4 Bxf3
17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. exf3 Qxf3 {and, with an active queen and a strong passed
pawn, Black is not worse.}) 16... Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxe2 $132 {. Both sides have
increased their control on "their" squares (White on dark squares and Black on
light squares). Strategically, White seems to be better, but the vulnerability
of his king invites to caution.}) 15... Rb8 {As frequently happens, the queen
is well developed on the initial square. The f6-bishop is over-protected and
the a5-square is kept under control, enabling an eventual knight move to
harrass the enemy queen. At the same time, the presence of the bishop on g4 is
very useful, because it inhibits the moving away of the other knight. In fact,
Black maintains the dynamic equilibrium by attacking both enemy knights with
his bishops.} 16. Qa4 {Somehow, moving again with the queen does not seem to
be right from an abstract point of view.} ({Now,} 16. Nb5 {is less effective
than in a previous comment, but certain accuracy is required from Black.} Bxc3
$1 (16... Bxf3 $6 17. exf3 $1 d4 (17... Bxc3 18. Rxd5 $1 $16) 18. Kg2 $5 {It
is important to defend the f3-pawn.} (18. Rd2 Qb6 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Qxb6 Nxf3+
21. Kg2 axb6 22. Kxf3 Bxc3 23. bxc3 $11) 18... Qd7 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4
21. Rd2 Rfd8 22. Rad1 $16) 17. bxc3 (17. Nxc3 Bxf3 18. exf3 d4 $13) (17. Rxd5
Qe7 18. Qxc3 Qxe2 19. Rg5 f6 20. Nbd4 Nxd4 21. Nxd4 Qe4 22. Re1 Qxe1+ 23. Qxe1
fxg5 $13) 17... Qe7 18. Nbd4 Bxf3 $11 {After getting rid of his potentially
"bad" bishop, Black is OK. The weakness of the d5 and c3-pawns (and that of
the c4 and d4-squares) compensate for eachother.}) ({I would think that} 16.
Rd2 $5 {is the most logical continuation, continuing the mobilisation of
forces and increasing the latent pressure against the central pawn.} Re8 17.
Rad1 Na5 (17... Re4 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Bxf6 $1 $14) (17... a6 {[%cal Gd8d6]} 18.
Nc2 $14 Rxe2 19. Rxe2 Bxf3 20. Ba5 $1 $14) 18. Bxa5 Qxa5 19. Kg2 {The position
remains interesting. Black's bishops continue to keep the enemy knights under
pressure, but White maintains his overall stability. It is hard to give a
final assesment, but I assume that for a strategic player White's position
would be slightly more appealing.[%cal Gh2h3]}) 16... Bxf3 $1 {A good moment
to carry out this exchange.} 17. exf3 {An ambitious, but strategically risky
decision.} (17. Nxf3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Re8 19. Rd2 Qf6 20. Qb3 b6 $132 {[%csl Rc3,
Rd5,Re2][%cal Gb8d8,Gc6a5]}) 17... Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Qd7 {Black has a passed pawn
in the centre, but White's king seems to be better defended than his rival,
because of the extra pawn on this wing. Aronian's main plan is to block the
enemey queenside pawns on dark squares and then simplify to an ending where
the bishop could attack them with Bb8. However, if this plan fails, the future
looks promising for Black, who can combine the threat of advancing the d4-pawn
with a kingside attack.} 19. b4 b6 20. Rac1 Rbc8 21. Bb2 Rfd8 22. Rc2 Ne7 23.
Rxc8 Nxc8 24. b5 Ne7 25. Qb3 Nf5 {From here, the knight 1) overprotects the
g7-square, 2) sustains the further advance of the passed pawn, 3) puts the
enemy kingside under pressure. Could we ask for more than that?} 26. a4 h5 27.
h3 Qe6 28. Kg2 Qe2 $1 {This brave intrusion of Her majesty puts White into
some trouble.[%cal Gd5d4]} 29. g4 $6 {He should not have weakened his own king
while there are queens on board still.} ({Accepting that things had gone
slightly wrong would have been wiser. White is worse after} 29. Bd4 Qc4 30. Qd3
Qxd3 31. Rxd3 Nxd4 32. Rxd4 Kf8 $15 {but he could try to generate some
counterplay on the kingside, where he still has an extra-pawn.[%cal Gf8c5,
Gf3f4,Gg3g4,Gg2f3]}) 29... Nh4+ (29... Ne3+ $2 30. Qxe3 Qxd1 31. Bxg7 $1 $16)
30. Kg3 Ng6 31. gxh5 Ne7 32. Kg2 Nf5 33. Bd4 Qe7 34. Qd3 Qg5+ 35. Kh2 Re8 36.
Bb2 Re3 $5 {This spectacular move is probably not the best.} (36... Qf4+ $1 37.
Kh1 (37. Kg1 $2 Ne3 38. fxe3 Qg3+ 39. Kf1 Qxf3+ 40. Kg1 Qg3+ 41. Kf1 Rxe3 $19)
(37. Kg2 $2 Nh4+ $19) 37... Ne3 38. Qe2 Nxd1 39. Qxe8+ Kh7 40. Qe2 Nxb2 41.
Qxb2 Qxf3+ $17) 37. fxe3 $2 $19 (37. Qxd5 $1 {would have paried the attack,
because Black faces problems avoiding the exchange of queens, while his rook
is hanging.[%cal Gd5d8]} Qf4+ 38. Kg1 Qg5+ (38... Re2 $6 39. Bc1 Qh4 40. Qd8+
$16 {would lead to the dream ending for White.[%csl Ra7,Rb6,Gb8]}) 39. Kh2 $11)
37... Qg3+ 38. Kh1 Qxf3+ 39. Kg1 Nxe3 40. Rd2 Qg3+ 41. Kh1 Qxh3+ 42. Kg1 Qg3+
43. Kh1 Qe1+ $1 44. Kh2 Qxd2+ 45. Qxd2 Nf1+ 46. Kg2 Nxd2 $19 {After a forced
and well-calculated sequence, Black has obtained decisive material advantage.
White's counterplay on the queenside will temporarily win one of the pawns
back, but this will not be enough to save the game.} 47. Be5 Ne4 48. Kf3 Nc5
49. Ke3 Nxa4 50. Kd4 Nc5 51. Kxd5 a6 52. bxa6 Nxa6 53. Kc6 Nc5 54. Bc7 Kh7 55.
Bxb6 Ne4 56. Be3 Nf6 57. Kd6 Nxh5 58. Ke5 Kg6 59. Bd2 f5 60. Be1 Kg5 0-1

