1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3 {By refraining from the immediate
occupation of the centre (d4 instead of, for instance, Nf3), White intends to
win a tempo for piece development, giving to the position a hypermodern
character. Of course, he can switch at any moment to well-known paths by
playing d4 later.} a6 {Black has a wide range of moves here, but none of them
is entirely free of drawbacks. After examining the practical material
available, I would recommend Black to refrain from the text move. However,
this might mean widening the opening repertoire (that is, adding some other
form of Slav than the Moldavian a6-line).} (4... Bg4 {allows White maintain an
advantage in space with} 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. Ne5 Be6 7. d4 $14 {Therefore, Black
should probably choose from one of the following three lines.}) ({In case of} 
4... Nbd7 {, apart from transposing to a normal Semi-Slav, White can try to
exploit his microscopical advantage in the symmetrical position arising after
[%cal Ge7e5]} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. d4) ({Or if} 4... e6 5. b3 Nbd7 {, then} 6. Qc2 (
6. cxd5 $6 {is not advisable now because of} exd5 $1) 6... Bd6 7. Bb2 {. There
are lots of games starting from this position, but I would just mention one
which was annotated by an expert of this whole white setup, Gurevich,M (2643)
-Savchenko,S (2583)/Vlissingen 1999/EXT 2000/[Gurevich,M] (1-0, 38).}) ({
Finally, there is} 4... g6 {, inviting White to the Schlechter variation.}) 5.
Qc2 b5 6. b3 Bg4 $6 {This certainly looks premature.} (6... e6 7. d4 {allows
White transpose to a favourable form of the Semi-Slav in which Black's early
queenside action has left him with weaknesses and no real counterplay.}) (6...
g6 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 7. Bb2 $5 (7. d4 Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {Although White
has basically lost a tempo, things are not easy for Black yet.} Nbd7 10. O-O
Bg7 11. cxd5 (11. Bd2 O-O 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Ne2 Ne4 14. Rfc1 e5 $132 {
Sargissian,G (2572)-Motylev,A (2634)/Istanbul 2003/CBM 096 (1/2-1/2, 36)})
11... cxd5 12. a4 b4 13. Ne2 a5 ({This looks like a loss of tempo, allowing
White take over the control of the c-file. However,} 13... Qa5 {does not
equalize either.} 14. Bb2 O-O 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Rc2 $1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1]}) 14.
Bb2 O-O 15. Rfc1 Qb6 16. Rc2 Rfc8 17. Rac1 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 e6 19. Ne5 Qa6 20. Nf4
Bh6 21. Nfd3 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Nd7 23. Bd4 $16 {Petronic,J (2450)-Matulovic,M 
(2420)/Vrnjacka Banja 1998/EXT 2002 (1/2-1/2, 51)}) 7... Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9.
Qxd3 Bg7 10. cxd5 Nxd5 (10... cxd5 $2 11. Nxd5 $1 $16) (10... b4 11. Na4 cxd5
12. O-O O-O 13. Rac1 $16) (10... O-O 11. e4 b4 12. Na4 cxd5 13. e5 Ne4 14. Rc1
$14) 11. O-O-O $5 (11. Nd1 Bxb2 12. Nxb2 O-O 13. O-O Nd7 {Makarov,M (2513)
-Asanov,T (2427)/St Petersburg 2002/EXT 2003 (1/2-1/2, 21). After the
simplifications, White's possibility of occupying the centre is less relevant.}
) 11... O-O (11... Nxc3 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bxc3 Bxc3 14. dxc3+ $36 {[%cal
Gf3g5,Gh2h4]}) 12. Nxd5 Bxb2+ 13. Kxb2 cxd5 14. Rc1 Qd6 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 15. Qc3
{[%cal Gh2h4]} Nd7 16. Qc7 $36) 7. Ne5 $36 {With his c6-pawn vulnerable and
his bishop exposed, Black faces serious problems already.} Bh5 $2 {This
blunder has been played before.} (7... Be6 8. Bb2 $14 Qc7 9. cxd5 (9. Ne2 $1
$14 {[%csl Rc7,Rf8][%cal Ge2f4,Gc4d5]}) 9... cxd5 10. Rc1 Nbd7 (10... Qxe5 11.
Nxb5 $18 {[%cal Gb5c7]}) 11. Bxb5 $6 {Here, this sacrifice is unsound.} (11.
Nxd7 $5 Qxd7 12. a4 $14 b4 $2 13. Nb5 $1 $18) 11... axb5 12. Nxb5 Qxc2 13. Rxc2
Nxe5 14. Nc7+ Kd8 15. Nxa8 Nd3+ (15... Bf5 $1 $17) 16. Ke2 Nxb2 17. Rxb2 Bc8
18. b4 $13 {Komarov,D (2540)-Prie,E (2516)/Chalons en Champagne 2007/CBM 116
ext (0-1, 48)}) 8. cxb5 cxb5 $6 $146 {Not suspecting anything.} ({In the
previous game where this position was seen, Black understood in time what was
cooking for him and played the "relatively better"} 8... Qc7 9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10.
bxc6 Qxc6 $16 {Agamaliev,G (2516)-Khaghani,M (2289)/Tehran 2005/CBM 104 ext 
(1-0, 30). , which allowed him play some more decent moves before resigning.})
9. Bxb5+ axb5 10. Nxb5 {The game is over. Black's insistence on playing on for
20 more moves may be regarded as some lack of respect for the opponent, but it
is not easy to resign before the game even started (although it is allowed by
the Sofia rule!)} e6 (10... Na6 11. Qc6+ Nd7 12. Nxd7 $18) 11. Nc7+ Ke7 12.
Nxa8 Nfd7 13. Ba3+ Kf6 14. Bb2 Nxe5 15. f4 Nbd7 16. Nc7 Bg6 17. Bxe5+ Nxe5 18.
fxe5+ Kxe5 19. Qc3+ Kf5 20. O-O+ Kg5 21. a4 Kh6 22. Rf3 Bf5 23. Raf1 Bd6 24.
Nb5 Bb8 25. Nd4 Be4 26. Rh3+ Kg6 27. d3 Bf5 28. Rhf3 Be5 29. Qe1 Bxd4 30. Rg3+
