1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O e6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. e4 {This tricky move order has been known for a
very long time. By delaying the development of his queen's bishop, White
retains the possibility of attacking the d6-pawn with Ba3, depending on
Black's answer.} Qc8 {Equally tricky.} ({White's main idea is revealed after} 
11... Qc7 12. Ba3 Nc5 13. e5 dxe5 14. Qxe5 {. It is far from clear whether
White has an objective advantage here, but his play seems to be easier in the
ensuing ending. See for instance Villamayor,B (2560)-Nguyen Anh Dung (2557)/
Manila 2001/CBM 083/[Stohl] (1/2-1/2, 57).}) (11... Qb8 {is less effective
than the text move because after} 12. Ba3 Nc5 13. e5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 dxe5 {White
has} 15. Bc6+ $1 {, depriving Black from the right to castle and retaining
strong initiative after} Kf8 16. Qe3 Ra7 17. b4 Ncd7 18. c5 {Stempin,P (2380)
-Ksieski,Z (2415)/Polanica Zdroj 1983/MCD (1-0, 36)}) 12. Bb2 {Having provoked
the slightly awkward placement of the enemy queen, White returns to the normal
course of development. Later, Black will need to spend a tempo on improving
the queen's position.} (12. Ba3 Nc5 13. e5 {would not work out so well now
because after} Bxf3 $1 14. Bxf3 dxe5 {the c6-square is defended by the black
queen.} 15. Qe3 ({Despite general belief before the computer era,} 15. Qxe5 {
is playable. After} Ncd7 $1 {White saves the game with[%csl Ga3,Ge5]} 16. Rxd7
Nxd7 17. Qxg7 Bf6 18. Ne4 $3 Bxg7 19. Nd6+ Kd8 20. Nxf7+ $1 $11 {and Black has
to agree to a draw by perpetual because} Kc7 $4 {unexpectedely leads to mate
in one with} 21. Bd6#) 15... Rb8 {Schneider,A (2425)-Wojtkiewicz,A (2550)/
Stara Zagora 1990/CBM 017 (0-1, 42). and White's compensation is questionable.}
) 12... O-O 13. Qe3 {In the systems where White develops with Bb2 and Qe3, his
rooks usually go to e2 and e1, in order to prevent the freeing move ...d5 in
view of e5. This means that the loss of time provoked by ...Qc8 may be
compensated by the early commitment of White's king's rook. However, Bu had
some unexpected plan in mind, where his rooks belong to d1 and c1.} Re8 {In
the English Hedgehog, the optimal placement of Black's rooks depends on far
from obvious details. Given the fact that Ivanchuk could not foresee Bu's plan
(as far as I know, it had only been played once before, in a worse form for
White, leading him to defeat), his last move seems very natural, because it
creates some pressure against the white queen (in view of an eventual ...d5).}
({Anticipating the further course of events,} 13... Rd8 {comes into
consideration. For instance:} 14. Rac1 Qc7 15. h3 {Same plan as in the game,
never tried in this position, though.} ({In case of} 15. Nd4 {Black can return
to the normal regrouping with} Re8 16. h3 Rad8 {, for instance} 17. Re1 Qb8 18.
Rb1 Bf8 19. a4 g6 20. Ba3 Bg7 $13 {and Black has achieved a comfortable
position in Bukal,V (2422)-Markus,R (2584)/Djakovo 2005/CBM 106 ext (0-1, 53)})
15... Rac8 16. Nh2 Qb8 17. Ng4 Ba8 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Na4 Bxb2 20. Nxb2 {and
now, having the d6-pawn more securely defended, Black can play} b5 $132) 14.
Rac1 Qc7 15. h3 $5 {This move is usually played in order to secure the queen
on h3, but this game will add new dimensions to the apparently modest pawn
move.[%cal Gf3h2,Gh2g4]} ({Once again,} 15. Nd4 {is not dangerous for Black.}
Rac8 16. h3 Qb8 (16... Bf8 17. Re1 g6 18. Rcd1 Qb8 19. Qd2 {1/2-1/2 Bischoff,K
(2541)-Lutz,C (2643)/Altenkirchen 2001/CBM 087}) 17. g4 h6 18. Qg3 Nc5 19. f3
Bd8 $5 {An original regrouping, justified by the awkward placement of the
white queen.} 20. h4 Bc7 21. g5 d5 22. Qh3 Nh5 23. Qg4 g6 24. cxd5 Bf4 $36 {
Popov,R (2470)-Notkin,M (2478)/Moscow 1999/EXT 2001 (0-1, 37)}) 15... Rac8 ({
Here, too, placing a rook on d8 would have made sense.} 15... Rad8 16. Nh2 Qb8
17. Ng4 Ba8 18. Nxf6+ ({The only game where Bu's manoeuvre had been played went
} 18. Ne2 Nxg4 19. hxg4 h6 $1 {Blocking the g4-pawn and preventing White from
increasing his advantage of space.} 20. Rc2 Ne5 21. f3 d5 $1 $132 {Espig,L 
(2445)-Womacka,M (2430)/Germany 1993/GER-chT2 (0-1, 33)}) 18... Bxf6 19. Na4
Bxb2 20. Nxb2 {. Again,} b5 {offers Black acceptable play, although in the
previous similar line the rooks seem to be better placed on c8 and d8.}) 16.
Nh2 Qb8 17. Ng4 {The point is that, after the exchange of one pair of knights,
Black faces some problems defending his d6- and b6-pawns. We have a slight
paradox here, because the exchange of pieces usually favours the player who
lacks space.} Ba8 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Na4 Be7 ({In the absence of a rook on d8,
} 19... Bxb2 20. Nxb2 $14 {offers White some initiative, because of the threat
Qd4.}) 20. e5 {Finally, White has managed to carry out this pawn break,
several moves after the opening has finished. This ensures him some initiative,
but maybe not an objective advantage yet.} Bxg2 21. exd6 $5 (21. Kxg2 Nxe5 22.
Bxe5 dxe5 23. Qxb6 Qa8+ 24. Kg1 Bg5 25. Rb1 e4 $132) 21... Bxd6 ({The tempting
} 21... Bxh3 {does not seem to work out well for Black:} 22. dxe7 Qb7 (22...
Rxe7 $2 23. g4 $3 {This elegant move traps the bishop. The pawn is taboo
because of Qg5, while[%csl Gh3]} b5 {can be met by} 24. Ba3 $1 $18) 23. f3 Rxe7
24. Rxd7 $1 Rxd7 25. Nxb6 Bf5 26. Nxd7 Qxd7 27. g4 Bg6 28. g5 $1 {Preventing ..
.f6, which would secure the g7-square and prepare an expansion in the centre.
[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge3e5]} Qd6 29. f4 $5 (29. Qe5 Qxe5 30. Bxe5 {offers Black
some counterplay after} f6 $5 31. gxf6 gxf6 32. Bxf6 Rf8) 29... Kf8 30. Qe5
Qxe5 31. Bxe5 $14 {and White's passed pawns preserve their mobility, while
Black's kingside is blocked.}) 22. Kxg2 Nc5 23. Nc3 $1 {The exchange of
knights would solve Black's problems of coordination.} Be5 $2 $16 {Rather
careless. With his king's rook passively placed, Black is not ready to display
such activity.} ({It was not too late yet to take the d-file under control with
} 23... Red8 $5 {for instance} 24. Rc2 (24. b4 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Gb4]}) 24... Qb7+
25. Kg1 Be7 {and Black's position is entirely viable.}) 24. b4 Nb7 (24... Qb7+
25. f3 Nd7 26. Rxd7 Qxd7 27. Qxe5 $16) 25. Qxb6 Rxc4 26. Na4 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 $16
{With his knight passively placed, his back rank vulnerable and his a6-pawn
weak, Black can hardly resist to the invasion of the enemy forces.} Bxb2 28.
Nxb2 Qa8 29. Qc6 Nd6 30. Qxa8 Rxa8 31. Rc6 Nf5 32. Rc7 h5 33. Nd3 h4 34. g4 Nd4
35. a4 f6 36. Nc5 e5 37. a5 Ne2 38. Ne6 Nf4+ 39. Nxf4 exf4 40. Rc6 {This move
allows Black some activity, which will eventually prove sufficient to save
this difficult ending.} (40. Rb7 $5 Rd8 (40... Kh7 41. Kf3 {loses a pawn
without any counterplay.}) 41. b5 $1 axb5 (41... Rd5 {does not change anything,
because it fails to create a threat. White can first carry out his kingside
plan with} 42. Kf3 $1 Kh7 43. Kxf4 {, and only now think about bxa6.} axb5 44.
a6 b4 45. a7 Ra5 46. Ke3 $18) 42. a6 Ra8 43. a7 Kh7 {With a pawn on the
seventh rank, White is winning, if only he can eliminate the dangerous b-pawn
and keep the relatively slow black counterplay on the opposite wing under
control.} 44. Kf3 b4 45. Ke4 $1 {Ignoring the f4-pawn, of course.} Kh6 46. Kd4
g5 ({In the event of} 46... f3 {the white king can go straight to the own pawn
with} 47. Kc5 $1 b3 48. Kb6 $18 {and Black's counterplay is one move too slow.
[%cal Gb6a6]}) 47. f3 b3 48. Kc3 Kg6 (48... f5 49. gxf5 g4 50. fxg4 f3 {would
lose too much material, allowing White change plans with} 51. Kd3 $1 $18 {
After the exchange of the b- and a-pawns, his kingside advantage will be
decisive anyway.}) 49. Kxb3 f5 50. gxf5+ Kxf5 51. Kc4 g4 52. fxg4+ Ke4 53. Kc5
f3 54. Rf7 Ke3 55. Kb6 $18) 40... Kf7 41. g5 Kg6 42. gxf6 gxf6 43. Kf3 Kg5 44.
Rc5+ f5 45. Rc6 Rb8 46. Rb6 Ra8 47. Ke2 Re8+ 48. Kd3 Re4 49. Kc3 Re2 50. Rxa6
Rxf2 51. Rd6 f3 52. Rd1 Kf4 53. Kb3 Re2 54. a6 Re3+ 55. Kc4 f2 56. Rf1 Kg3 57.
b5 Ra3 {Black's counterplay has become too threatening and White decided to
force a draw.} 58. Kb4 Ra2 59. Kb3 Ra5 60. Kb4 Ra2 61. Kb3 Ra5 1/2-1/2

